layout: layouts/service-subpage.njk
title: "Federal Retirement Tax Planning: Avoid the Retirement Year Tax Trap | Capital Wealth"
description: "Federal retirees face unique tax challenges. Learn about the retirement year tax trap, pension taxation, TSP withdrawal strategies, Roth conversions, IRMAA avoidance, and optimal retirement timing."
serviceTag: "federal"
breadcrumbs:
  - { name: "Home", url: "/" }
  - { name: "Services", url: "/services/" }
  - { name: "Federal Employee Benefits", url: "/services/federal-benefits/" }
  - { name: "Federal Retirement Taxes", url: "/services/federal-benefits/federal-retirement-taxes/" }
faqSchema:
  - question: "Is my FERS pension fully taxable?"
    answer: "Nearly all of your FERS pension is taxable as ordinary income. A small portion of each payment represents a return of your after-tax employee contributions and is not taxed, but for most retirees this non-taxable portion is minimal. The vast majority of your FERS annuity will be reported as taxable income on your federal tax return each year, and potentially on your state return as well depending on where you live."
  - question: "What is the best month to retire for tax purposes?"
    answer: "December 31st is the optimal retirement date for most federal employees from a tax perspective. By retiring on the last day of the year, you push all pension income, TSP withdrawals, and Social Security benefits into the following calendar year — a year in which you have no salary income. This avoids stacking retirement income on top of a partial year of salary, which can push you into higher tax brackets and trigger Medicare IRMAA surcharges. The potential savings range from $5,000 to $15,000 or more in a single year."
  - question: "How can I avoid IRMAA surcharges on Medicare?"
    answer: "IRMAA surcharges are based on your modified adjusted gross income from two years prior. To avoid them, manage your income strategically in the years that will be used for IRMAA determination. This means carefully timing TSP withdrawals, Roth conversions, and other income events. If you experience a life-changing event such as retirement that significantly reduces your income, you can file Form SSA-44 to appeal and request that Medicare use your more recent, lower income instead of the higher income from two years ago."
  - question: "Should federal employees do Roth conversions?"
    answer: "Roth conversions can be extremely valuable for federal employees, especially during lower-income years between retirement and the start of Required Minimum Distributions at age 72-73. The window between retirement and RMDs often represents the lowest tax bracket years of your life. Converting traditional TSP funds to Roth during this period — while staying within lower tax brackets and below IRMAA thresholds — can save significant taxes over your lifetime. As of January 2026, in-plan Roth conversions are available directly within the TSP."
  - question: "Are TSP withdrawals taxable?"
    answer: "Traditional TSP withdrawals are 100% taxable as ordinary income. Every dollar you withdraw from your traditional TSP balance will be added to your taxable income for that year. Roth TSP withdrawals, however, are completely tax-free if they are qualified distributions — meaning your Roth account has been open for at least 5 years and you are age 59 and a half or older. This fundamental difference makes Roth conversion planning a critical component of federal retirement tax strategy."
